{"/service/ndnp/ncu/batch_ncu_dowe_ver01/data/sn92073229/00332891868/1958050801/0360.xml":{"full_text":"Page Two\nThe Chapel Hill Weekly\nChapel Hill, North Carolina\n124 IturWTiH-T Tflephon* 0-1271 or M*l\nPoUiokKi Errrt Moolii end Ttiarndoy\nBy TW Q\u00bbp*l Hill Poblmhmg Cowpoo?. l\u00bbt\nLovis G*aves Contr. bul Editor\nJoe Jonts Managing Editor\nOkwllx Caxtpbxu. General Manager\nJiME Carraarr Advertising Manager\nCha*lton Cam*\u00abk-*. Mechanic*. Sup:\nm MOt\nt at oar. attic* Ca* pa', ii\u2014 Ncf-t uoO\u00bb\ntr< Vr i r~\u00bb\nSUBSCRIPTION RATES\nIe Ora-ft Goss:}\" Year KW\n(6 m\u00abKih 9ZJ2&: S IIJP)\nOoUii*; of Oranfrt Cosnty ej tte Y enr\nStave? of N. C-, Va_ aac S. C,\nOther State* end Da\", a! Cohunfca j>-W\nCaattk Mexiro, Sooth Aserua 70*'\nEcrop*\nThe Revolting Detail? in Crime News*\nThe practice of every profession c&la.-\nfor a good deal of scolding. Doctor*\nscold Ur for eating too much anc not\nthk'.ng regular exercise and disregard\ning tneir orders about mediemes and\nfailing to undergo regular examina\ntions. Lawyers scold us for not keeping\nour records straight and for not making\nour wills. Preachers scold ire\u2014well,\nI\u2019ll not try to enumerate all th\u00ab fault\nthey find in us; the sad figure we cut\nas we go about our daily kfe is urr.m*-.\nup well in the line in the prayer boos\nwhich declares that we are ait misera\nble sinners and there is no health in us.\nBut the profession that stands far\nabove these and all others, that ea.\nholds the championship, ir. reproving,\nreproaching, censuring, and the giving\nof advice is that of the newsi\u00abper edi\ntor.\nThe newspaper edit r e?. I\nviction that there is no other profes\nsion and no trade or occupation of a:\nsort that he doesn\u2019t know how to\nduct better than the max. who ha-\nbrought up in it. And he is more than\nwilling to share m.\u00bb knowledge with\none and all. Hi.- generosity in this r*\nspect Ls unexcelled. 1 my f\u00a3ih*\\e fre\nquently counseled the ol the\nUnited States ana Congress tar\niff, taxation, management of the\ngovernment ftpart merits, subsidizing\nof highways and schools, and the most\nintricate questions of foreign policy.\nAnd 1 have been equally generous .r;\npointing out to state, county, and mu\nnicipikl governments what they have\ndone wrong and what they ought to do\nto get back on the right track.\nWhat\u2019s true of me as a profferer ol\nadvice- is of course true of the brother\nhood of editors in general. J know the\nfrom my reading of many newspaj<er.'\nranging from the New York Times and\nthe Christian Science Moiutor, and th*\nBaltimore Sun, and the Manchester\nGuardian and the Jyundon 'lime down\nto the most obscure small town weer\nlies. Ali of us. editor are consecrated,\nor, to use a word popular in these day.-,\ndedicated, to the mission of setting\nother people right.\nExcept in letter.- -to-lht.-editor, by\nmeans of which we are sometimes re\nminded that there is such a thing as a\nnewspaper\u2019s having to take it as well\nas being privileged to hand it out, there\nis little said counter to our criticism\nand advice. These letters do not go far\nto reduce our complacent;. first, be\ncause a considerable proportion of them\nexpress agreement with our opinions\nand thereby make us more convinced\nthan ever that we are God\u2019s own agent*\nin the guidance we give to our neigh\ni-iors, and, second, because not one per\nson in ten thousand, or many more\nthousands than ten, among those who\ndisagree with us, takes the trouble to\nwrite a letter to tell us so.\nI sometimes wonder whether or not\nnewspaper editors, if they could ap\npear unseen, like H. G. Wells\u2019 Invisible\nMan, in homes, or in any gatherings of\nnewspaper readers, and hear what peo\nple think of some of the practices of\nnewspapers would be made ashamed of\nthemselves. I suspect not, because they\nhave been rationalizing their faults,\nppd repeating plausible-sounding argu\nments m defense of them, so long that\nit is practically impossible to persuade\nthem that there is anything seriously\nwrong with what they publish.\nAn editor with real authority-\u2014and\nthere are many such though they may\nhave no ownership in their papers\u2014has\ncontrol not only of the editorial page\nbut also of all the other pages\u2014news,\nfeatures, everything. He even has the\npower to ban advertising that he de\nffAf does not measure up to high stan-\ndiirds of truth and decency.\nThe part of newspapers that I hear\ncondemned moet often and most bitter\nly i- the crime news\u2014the reports of\nmurders, rapes, and sex scandals. The\ncriticism spoken by a neighbor of mine\none day last week is typical of those I\nhave heard many a time. I do not give\nhis exact words but what he said was\nsubstantially as follows:\n\"I don\u2019t believe news ought to be\nsuppressed i-ecause it is about crime.\nNot ever, when the crime is of a dis\ngusting character. But what 1 object\nto is the way the pa{\u00abers parade it.\nspreading it all over the front page\nwith big headlines, and relating in col\numn after column all the nauseating,\nrevolting detail.- This is without doubt\nan affront u> decency and I don't think\nthe paper- Cave any right to subject\nus to it.\u201d\n'I thin i> a fair criticism.\nThe chief defense that 1 have heard\nfrom newspapermen is that \u201cnewspa\npers ought to print the truth.\u201d An\nother defense is that \u201cit\u2019s our business\nto give the people the sort of news the\npeople want.\u201d\nThe newspaper* can certainly print\nthe truth about crime without going\ninto a. details. As for\ngiving the people \u201cthe sort of news the\npeople war.*.,\u201d that simply means kneel\ning down before, and worshipping, the\ngreat god Circulation.\nThe greater the circulation \u2014the\nhigher th*- rates that can be. charged\nfor advertising therefore the greater\nthe revenue.\nThe da., new-papers of North aro-\nJina\u2014and it these that I\u2019m writing\nabout\u2014ar*-. r, the main, pr- j*-rous.\nSom< of tho\u2014\u25a0 w itr. the dirtiest stuff in\nthem are the wealthiest. Their owner\narid editors could easily get along, and\ncon*inue to enjoy the comfort- of life,\nwithout the part of their income that is\nto be credited to the dirty stuff that\nthey print day after day.\nEvery nod y ought to approve thor\noughly of the newspap* r- doing all\nthey car, proj**rly do to increase their\ncirculatior 'The increase ir. a new spa\nper c:n-u;a\u2019.i'-r and it- consequent\nability to increase its revenue, not only\nbenefits it but also, because it\nmain- ;\u00ab0.--ibic the production of a\nnewspaper of high quality, is a distinct\nbenefit to the community:\nI said \u201cail they can properly do.\u2019\u2019\nSurUy not to be included in that are\nthe sordid, repulsive details that the\nwspaper&r and I -am thinking\nesjAs-ial!;. of the papers that are thrown\not! rnv porch every morning -put in\nth* r reports of crime.\u2014L.G.\nRandom Remarks\nt rom the\nAutobiography ol MichH dr .Moulaagn*-\nTar !,y or.*- thing with another, I fan\nc. that men as often praise me without\nr*-. as condemn me. It seems to me\nthat they have given me, from child\nrosi a place in rank and honor above\nrather than below my due. 1 should\nfind myself more at a-*- in a country\nre titles and rank were either better\nregulated or altogether despised. In\nour .society, as soon as, a dispute over\npn-eedcnce concerned with where you\nar*- to sit or walk ari-e- exceeds three\nretorts' politeness ends. The l>etter\nto avoid such annoying disputes. I\nnever stickle at giving or taking a\nplace out of turn. No man ever de\nsir*-d to precede me without my yielding\nat once.\nThe simple peasants are worthy peo\nple and so are the philosophers\u2014or\nthose we now consider as such\u2014strong\nand clear natures enriched with a great\nstore of useful knowledge. The mon\ngrels like myself and a great many\nmore, who have disdained the ignorance\nof the one and can\u2019t achieve the knowl\nedge of the other\u2014who sit between\ntwo stools \u2014are dangerous, useless, and\na nuisance; it is they who trouble the\nworld. Therefore I seek as best 1 can\nto return to the first and natural con\ndition, from which I have fruitlessly\ntried to depart.\n\nAge of Super Progress?\n(Sou Ultra PUn. Pilot)\nGadgetry (if there is such a word)\nnever ceases.\nWhile people like us are sitting on\ntheir porch steps watching bee* work\nover the azalea flowers and feeling\nmore or less at peace with the world,\nsomebody is thinking up another fiend\nish way to make life easier, yet at the\nsame time a great deal more compli\ncated, for simple souls.\nThe fruit of sorpe such gadgeteer\u2019s\nefforts was illustrated in a New York\nTHE CHAPEL HILL WEEKLY\n\u201cIt Seems He Has A Bear By The Tail\u2014Or Vice Versa**\nNow and Then By Bill Prouty\nall this talk about there be\ning a big recession sort of make you\nsmile? if you\u2019re 35 year of ag*- or\nolder, it might even make you bust out\nlaughing.\nOs course, there may be a little\ntightening up on all that extra spend\ning money that's: beer floating around\never since the end War 11.\nCertain signs crop up now and then.\nOnce in a while you\u2019ll see a man look\ning at the second line in some make of\nmanufactured good-. He still buys the\nfirst line, but he\u2019ll tak* a look at all the\nprices. Now and then you\u2019ll hear a\nshopper asking a clerk if he has some\nthing just a little les.- expensive than\nthe article he's being shown. And some\ntimes you\u2019ll even see a customer count\ning his change after he\u2019s made a pur\nchase.\nAnd then there\u2019s that small car trend\nthat we\u2019re going through nowadays, in\naway, you might say this is a reces\nsion. Even the fact that Americans\nwill take seriously automobiles only\nabout two-thirds as large as they\u2019ve\nbeen used to may js i haps be considered\nas some kind of r> ion. And foreign\nBars at that!\nBut on a second look, you usually\nfind that Dad is driving the new little\nbuggy, while Ma or Junior is still pilot\ning the big job. So Dad\u2019s argument\nthat he got the little car because it was\nso cheap to drive doesn\u2019t ring quite\ntrue. The fact that the small auto,\nwhat with transportation, duty and\nother costs, isn\u2019t exactly cheap, never\nseems to enter the discussion. In oth\ner words, we\u2019re buying extra transpor\ntation because it\u2019s cheaper to operate\nthan our old transportation, which\nwe\u2019re also keeping. This is recession?\nMaybe so, but do you know that you\ncould buy, delivered in Chapel Hill, the\nbest stock Chevrolet made for right at\nSBOO in 1928 and 1929, when cost of\nliving prices were at an all-time peak up\nto that time? Coffee was 44c a pound\nand butter waa selling for 50c. You\ncould get bacon for 38c per pound, and\nsmpkers were puffing at the rate of\ntwo packs of their favorite brand for\ndepartment store ad in Sunday\u2019s i\u00bb-\npers: an electric fire lighter.\nCan you beat that? It\u2019s a ring of\nmetal on a handle. You plug it in and\nthe metal gets hot and lights your\nwood fire \u201cevery time.\u201d\nWell, reckon some folks would like\nit. For our part, we wouldn\u2019t swap a\nfew lightwood splinters for any fin\nlighter that waa ever manufactured.\nMort Lawrence: Home is a place\nwhere we* are treated the best and\ngrumble the most.\n25c. while Wesson oii was 50c a quart.\nA comparison bi these before-the\non price *me of our pres\nent day \"recession\u201d prices is interest\ning. instead of 44c coffee, we have\n80c coffee (not too long ago it was\nover 1 1 j, while butter is now 70c\nagainst 50c then. Cigarettes cost near\nly twice as much now as they did m\nthose days, while that SBOO Chevrolet\nof 30 years ago would now set you back\naround three times that amount.\nNow. if it\u2019s a recession you\u2019re look\ning for, let\u2019s turn to Vol. 12 of the\nChapel Hill Weekly and look at some\nof the prices listed in the ads during\nthe spring of 1934, right in the middle\nof the depression hereabouts.\nCoffee was -elling for 20c, while but\nter wa.- going for 28c and bacon for 23c.\nSugar was 48c for 10 {rounds, while\nWesson oil was 39c a quart. Dressed\nhens were going for 21c and (believe it\nor not) chuck roast could be had at 15c\na pound.\nHot dogs were waiting on the grills\nfor five cents apiece, and bread was\neither 10c or 5c a loaf.\nYou could get a g*Bal ts-er f\u00ab,r 10c a\nbottle or can, and the best for 15c.\nCigarettes (for those who didn\u2019t roll\ntheir own either by hand or with a roll\ning machine) were ten and fifteen cents\na pack for real tobacco and no filter.\nYou could go to movies for 30c and\nyou could get a pair of g'ssl shoes for\nless than $5. Unless you were big eat\ner, you could get all you wanted for 25\nor 30 cents a meal.\nA man who paid over $25 for a suit\nof clothes or $12.50 for an overcoat waa\nin the upper bracket around here; while\na buck a day would rent you a small\nhouse.\nTalk about a recession, we really had\none back in those days in Chapel Hill.\nAnd, making things tougher here than\nin d lot of other towns hen-abouts, all\nthe University employees, faculty and\nadministrative, had been given a 33 per\ncent cut in salary in 1933!\nNow no one ever wants to see those\nridiculous prices in the Weekly axis of\nthe future. And, of course, we all hope\nthat any change in the salary and\nwages of all employees will be up and\nnot down. And there\u2019s no reason to\nbelieve that we\u2019ll ever see the likes of\nthose days again.\nBut aren\u2019t you just a little bit glad\nthat you once bought chuck roast for\n15c a pound, and purchased, or rode in,\na brand new S6OO automobile, or munch\ned on a five-cent hot dog? And all of\nthat on 15 to 20 bucks a week!\nAnd aren\u2019t you just a little bit weary\nof this $2,500-automobile, 18c-loaf-of\nbread \u201crecession\u201d talk we\u2019re struggling\nthrough now?\nI Like Chapel Hill\nBy Billy Arthur\nWe'll admit that Bart Bartholomew does as much\nwork a.- any person we know who writes l'or a living.\nAs public information officer of the University Division\nof Health Affairs, he puts in far more time on his job\nthan the 40 hours a week generally expected of state\nemployees. On the side, he averages writing six book\nreviews a week, does free lance newspaper and magazine\narticles under his own name and two pseudonyms, han\ndles photography assignments for a number of publica\ntions and is writing a novel that he says, \u201cshould do\nwell with the cigar store and poolroom trade.\u201d Being\nfond of sleep, we haven\u2019t checked on this personally, but\nour milkman and paper boy say he Ls often working in\nhis yard at 5:30 a.m. and may be found at his office at\n7:30 on Sunday mornings. The other morning when\nwe opened our copy of the Durham Morning Herald, we\nsaw two stories in the feature section, side by side, with\nBart\u2019s by-line on both. One story concerned the UNG\nSchool of Public Health and the other was on guided\nmissiles at Qooke Air Force Base in California. We\u2019ve\nmarked as an error in the Herald composing\nroom. Bart just isn\u2019t covering that much territory.\n\nArnold King told UNO aJumni recently that classes\nmight get so crowded that instructors and professors\nwrxild have to teach early in the* morning and late in\nthe evening.\nThe dean forgets that we have not yet closed Finley\nGolf Course and that just because he might wake up at\ndaybreak not everyone else does.\n\nOne of the best kickers ever to perform in Kenan\nStadium was Bud Wallace.\nHe\u2019s been back in Chapel Hill off and on for the past\nfour months. Still kicking. This time it\u2019s about the\nweather. His firm of Faulkner and Wallace have the\ncurb and gutter contract in Greenwood.\n\nSen. Ed Lanier had K. P. Williams buttonholed on\n'Continued on Page 5)\nCHAPEL HILL CHAFF,\n(Continued from P\u00bbfe 1)\npetters for their playtime.\u201d\nRecently, in consequence of what I\u2019ve been reading\nabout the importation of smaller sizes, I have been more\ninterested in looking at automobiles than 1 used to be.\nWhen I was talking along Hooper Lane day before\nyesterday and came alongside a small sedan, i stopped\nto examine it more closely. A girl sat at the wheel.\n\u201cI\u2019ve just been admiring your car,\u201d I said. She\nsmiled politely but made no reply. Then 1 saw that\nthere wa.- another occupant of the driver\u2019s seat. It was\na boy with his head on the girl\u2019s shoulder. 1 had not\nmeant to be prying but now, being close by, 1 couldn\u2019t\nhelp seeing him. He, too, smiled and said nothing.\nNeither gave any sign of embarrassment. I was the\nonly one of us three who was embarrassed.\nThis incident reminds me of an old-time friend of\nmine, long since dead, Bob Neville. He was in the\nSpanish War. After the war he floated about and\nsaw a Jot of the world. When I came back home ini\nl'J3l after living in New York he had a job as rural\nmail carrier. He would start out in the morning and\nhis day\u2019s work would be over by about 12:30. Almost\nevery day, after eating dinner, he would come down to\nEubanks\u2019 drugstore and sit on the bench by the soda\nfountain to the left as you entered the store. The soda\nfountain is no longer there but the benches remain.\nBob would spend the afternoon l*>oking through the\nbig window at the passing life on Franklin Street and\ngossiping with whoever might come and sit on the\nbench with him or on the adjacent window seat.\nOne of the street sights he used to enjoy was the\nyoung women, University co-eds and others, who,\nthough the\u00a3 didn\u2019t know it, formed a parade for his\nbenefit. He also enjoyed voicing his disapproval of the\nscantiness of their clothing. Sometimes he threw in\ncritical remarks on the behavior of modern girls and\nboys. A likeable trait of Bob\u2019s was his fondness, at\ntimes, for laughing at himself.\nHe said to me one afternoon when I sat beside him:\n\u201cQueer thing. Did you ever think about it? How,\nwhen a fellow\u2019s young he wants to have all the fun he\ncan. Then when he gets old it makes him sore to see\nyoung folks havin\u2019 fun. \u2019Course, we\u2019re just jealous of\n\u2019em, that\u2019s all.\u201d\nAnswering Bob\u2019s question, Yes, I have. I\u2019ve thought\nabout it often. One night several years ago 1 got a\nmegaphone from the room of a student lodger in our\nhouse, went out on the porch overlooking Hooper Lane,\nand shouted: \u201cBetters! Beware! President Gordon Gray\nis coming! Dean Weaver is coming! All petters, be\nware!\u201d 1 recall with shame the sound of starting mo\ntors after I made this brutal assault on youth\u2019s most\ntreasured pastime.\n1 am resolved that Pm not going to make any more\nmoves against petting. Let Dean Katherine Carmichael\nand Chancellor Aycock and Vice President Carmichael\nand President Friday, if want to, take cognizance'\nof the prevalence of this pastime, but they can leave me\nout of it.\nThere may be different ideas as to whether petting\ninterferes with community cleanliness and order, but\nanother practice of the petters certainly does. That is,\nthe throwing of paper cups, wrappings, bottles, tins, and\nother rubbish on the streets and in people\u2019s yards. This\nis disgusting and the University, which is in loco pa\nrentis for the students and therefore is projjerly to be\nheld responsible for their acts, should put an end to it.\nBUFFET EYERY SUNDAY 5:80-7:30\nThursday, May 8,19 fl","height":"26419","width":"19955"}}
